  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "3m0MRRv62SY3sJzRglLdkjeb6dk=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:35.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Real-time trigger: GSOC with polling fallback\n\nGSOC is sub-second \u2014 direct SOC sync with no Trojan mining on the hot path. Mining a signer targeting a peer's neighborhood costs roughly 10\u201330 s per (peer, collab) pair, but that cost is paid **once on collab creation/join** and never again.\n\n### Protocol\n\n1. Participant writes a new op \u2192 SwarmChannel pushes to their feed.\n2. Immediately after, a GSOC ping goes to each *other* participant's signer:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"type\": \"op-committed\",\n  \"collabId\": \"drive:<driveId>\" | \"doc:<driveId>:<docId>\",\n  \"writerAddress\": \"0xA\u2026\",\n  \"latestIndex\": { \"global\": 42 }\n}\n```\n\n3. Each recipient's SwarmChannel reacts by pulling that writer's feed on demand, **debounced ~300 ms** so a burst of ops coalesces into a single pull. This prevents a drag-reorder on a large list from triggering dozens of overlapping fetches.\n4. The timer-based poll remains as a **fallback** for participants who were offline when the ping was sent. When they come back, the next poll catches up any ops whose pings they missed.\n\nResult: sub-second live updates when everyone is online, eventual consistency otherwise.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:35.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:35.000Z"
    }
  },
